That's probably because plantigrade shoes have been a thing forever, so we know what they're supposed to look like. They fit neatly into our cultural understanding of things. Digitigrade also seems natural to us, because that's how many animals move, so it's got its place in anthro stuff. But digitgrade shoes? Yeah, those are rare. And between you and me, I think most plantigrade anthro's that are still depicted to have paw-like feet wouldn't fit normally into human footware, either. Especially the stuff we tend to perceive as elegant, because those are typically very slender, while paws tend to get depicted as fairly bulky.
